Notes on Pew Data

Pew info using Census - note from Pew on data: This analysis includes only counties with 10,000 or more residents in 2018. These counties account for 77% of the nations 3,142 counties and 99% of the U.S. population. - CITATION: Pew Research Center analysis of 2000 decennial census and 2018 Census Bureau population estimates. - official name of table: Population in U.S. counties where Hispanic, black, or indigenous people are a large share of residents - column names: percent of population that was one racial/ethnic group other than white in 2018 AND largest racial/ethnic group, 2018 - article: by Katherine Schaeffer - 2018: 151 US counties where Hispanics, blacks, and American Indians/Alaska Natives made up majority of pop - up from 110 in 2000 - 41 of new were black or Hispanic

#####-------------------------------------------------------------------------------#

#### General overview of buzz words ####

## pre-process: make a `quanteda` corpus from dataframe
speech_corpus <- corpus(speech_df, text_field = "text", docid_field = "url")

## pre-process: tokenize, clean, select n-grams
speech_toks_hispanic <- tokens(speech_corpus, 
    remove_punct = TRUE,
    remove_symbols = TRUE,
    remove_numbers = TRUE,
    remove_url = TRUE) %>% 
    tokens_tolower() %>%
    tokens_remove(pattern=c("joe","biden","donald","trump","president","kamala","harris")) %>%
    tokens_remove(pattern=stopwords("en")) %>%
    tokens_select(min_nchar=3) %>%
    tokens_ngrams(n=2, concatenator = " ") %>%
    tokens_select(pattern = c("hisp*", "communism", "latin*", "socialism", "dict*", "cuba*", "maduro", 
                              "castro*"), padding = TRUE)

print(speech_toks_hispanic)

TV ad spending per media market

state_ad <- media_mkt_df %>%
  rename(state = "Market State", 
         market = "Media Market", 
         total_airings = "Total Airings 9Apr20 to 11Oct20", 
         cost = "Est. Cost 9Apr20 to 11Oct29", 
         biden_airings = "Pro-Biden Airings 9Apr20 to 11Oct20", 
         trump_airings = "Pro-Trump Airings 9Apr20 to 11Oct20", 
         biden_adv = "Biden Ad Adv 28Sept20 to 11Oct20") %>%
  select(state, market, biden_airings, trump_airings, biden_adv) %>%
  filter(state %in% c("TX", "AZ", "KS", "WA", "CA", "FL", "NM"))
  
state_sums <- state_ad %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  summarise(total_ad_t = sum(trump_airings), 
            total_ad_b = sum(biden_airings)) %>%
  rename(Biden = "total_ad_b", 
         Trump = "total_ad_t") %>%
  gather(candidate, tot_ad, Trump:Biden) %>%
  mutate(log_ad = log(tot_ad))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
spend_tv <- ggplot(state_sums, aes(x = state, y = log_ad)) + 
    geom_bar(aes(fill = candidate), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red")) +
  labs(fill = "Candidate", 
       title = "2020 Presidential Election: Log TV Ad Airings Per State", 
       subtitle = "April 9th - October 20th",
       x = "State", 
       y = "Log Ad Airings", 
       caption = "Source: Wesleyan Media Project") +
  my_theme
